State of the application after implementing the articles feature and the most important learnings

Paragraph 1 — Scope and stack
This repo is a single-module Android app (:app) using Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, Material 3, Hilt (with KSP for Hilt and Moshi codegen), Retrofit + Moshi + OkHttp (with logging), Timber, Kotlin coroutines, StateFlow in the ViewModel, Coil for images, and Compose Navigation + hilt-navigation-compose. The Articles flow is wired end-to-end: ArticleApi / ArticleRepository call NewsAPI-style JSON (top-headlines under https://newsapi.org/v2/), ArticleModel.mapArticle maps ArticleData to presentation Article (including relative date strings), ArticleViewModel exposes ArticleUIState (Loading / Success / Error) with a fixed user-facing error string and technical errors logged, and ArticleScreen renders loading, error (with retry), and a list with images. MainActivity is @AndroidEntryPoint and shows ArticleScreen; CursorTrainingApplication is @HiltAndroidApp and plants Timber.DebugTree in debug; AndroidManifest includes INTERNET and the custom Application class. NEWS_API_KEY is supplied via root gradle.properties into BuildConfig.NEWS_API_KEY.

Paragraph 2 — Build and configuration facts
The project uses AGP 9.1 with android.builtInKotlin=false and android.newDsl=false in gradle.properties so the standalone Kotlin Android plugin and the Hilt Gradle plugin work together; the app module applies kotlin.android, kotlin.compose, Hilt, and KSP. app/build.gradle.kts sets kotlin { jvmToolchain(11) } to match Java 11 compile options. ./gradlew assembleDebug has completed successfully after the changes described in this thread. Gradle output has included deprecation warnings for those two Android properties and for the android { } DSL in app/build.gradle.kts, and a Moshi-related note about Kapt in codegen during the Java compile step; the configure step prints AGP built-in Kotlin / new DSL deprecation warnings.

Paragraph 3 — Files, pitfalls, and how to work safely
Key locations: version catalog gradle/libs.versions.toml; root build.gradle.kts (plugin aliases with apply false); app/build.gradle.kts (plugins, android block including buildConfig and debug/release NEWS_API_KEY fields, dependencies grouped by comment); gradle.properties (JVM args, Kotlin style, Android flags, NEWS_API_KEY); app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml; CursorTrainingApplication.kt; MainActivity.kt; articles/data/ (ArticleApi, ArticleData, ArticleSourceData, ArticlesResponse, ArticleRepository); articles/presentation/ (Article.kt with ArticleModel, ArticleUIState, ArticleViewModel); articles/ui/ArticleScreen.kt; di/NetworkModule.kt; res/values/strings.xml for article-related copy. Avoid surfacing raw exception messages in the UI (the ViewModel uses a fixed string for errors); keep API keys out of source by using gradle.properties / BuildConfig. To build, use ./gradlew assembleDebug from the project root (on Windows PowerShell, chain commands with ;, not &&, if the shell rejects &&).
